## What changed

The window-level **"Hide others"** reveal no longer AX-minimizes the app's other windows (which fired macOS's slow genie animation and made hovering between an app's windows feel sluggish). It now **parks each sibling off-screen instantly** by setting its AX position to a far down-right point, then un-parks + raises the target — so the result looks identical but happens with no animation.

- **Capture/restore is exact:** each non-minimized window's pre-summon position is captured in the session baseline and the persisted crash-safety-net snapshot; `restore`, `commit`, and restore-on-launch all move windows back to their original origin.
- **App-level hide is untouched** — `NSRunningApplication.hide()` has no per-window animation, which is why the bead noted the app level "works well."
- Windows the user had already minimized are left alone (never parked).

**Files:** `WindowControl.swift`, `LiveWindowSystem.swift`, `RevealState.swift` (production) plus the four test files (`FakeWindowSystem`, `WindowControlTests`, `RevealStateTests`, `RadialNavigatorTests`/`CommitTests`).

